c c Strict-decomp regression: faithful --compile of this CNF emits a circuit
c c whose model count + model SET are correct (5897, matches brute force) but
c c which violates strict d-DNNF decomposability: some AND node has two children
c c whose subtrees both mention var 16. Root cause: conflict-learned (redundant)
c c clauses can bridge variables that CompAnalyzer placed in different
c c sub-components (the analyzer only sees irreducible clauses). Propagation
c c inside one sub-component then sets a variable that "belongs" to another
c c sub-component, which leaks into the OR's arc-lits.
c c
c c ddnnf-cleanup REPAIRS this post hoc by default: its strict-decomp pass
c c scrubs the shared var from the child that doesn't force it (the other
c c child's models all imply that var-polarity, so the scrub preserves count
c c + model set). The first two RUN lines exercise the raw circuit (count
c c + set still correct), the rest assert that after cleanup the circuit is
c c strictly decomposable.
c c
c c Originally surfaced by `python3 tests/ddnnf_fuzz.py 500 --seed 207900131`.
c c
c c RUN: %solver --compile %t.nnf %s
c c RUN: %ddnnf_verify %t.nnf --cnf %s
c c RUN: %ddnnf_cleanup %t.nnf %t.clean.nnf
c c RUN: %ddnnf_verify %t.clean.nnf --cnf %s --check-decomposable --strict
p cnf 16 40
